\begin{abstract}

We investigate the emergence of color confinement and Regge trajectories
within the Hamiltonian Crystal framework, where the vacuum is modeled
as a discrete lattice of Fock-space excitations. We show that a linear
confinement potential naturally arises when color flux propagates through
discrete vacuum cells. The resulting flux tube behaves as a rotating
string, leading directly to the Regge relation $m^2 \propto J$ observed
in hadron spectroscopy. Numerical estimates using the QCD string tension
are consistent with experimental hadron mass spectra.

\end{abstract}

\section{Introduction}

One of the central features of Quantum Chromodynamics (QCD) is
color confinement. Quarks and gluons are not observed as free particles
but instead form bound states such as mesons and baryons.
Lattice QCD simulations show that the potential between color charges
grows linearly at large distances,

\begin{equation}
V(r) = \sigma r ,
\end{equation}

where $\sigma$ is the string tension.

Another important empirical observation is that hadrons lie on
approximately linear Regge trajectories,

\begin{equation}
m^2 \propto J ,
\end{equation}

where $m$ is the hadron mass and $J$ is its angular momentum.

In this work we show that both phenomena arise naturally
in the Hamiltonian Crystal framework.

\section{Hamiltonian Crystal Vacuum}

The Hamiltonian Crystal describes the vacuum as a collection
of discrete excitation modes,

\begin{equation}
H_{\text{vac}} =
\sum_n \Delta E_n a_n^\dagger a_n .
\end{equation}

Here $a_n^\dagger$ and $a_n$ are creation and annihilation
operators for vacuum modes, and $\Delta E_n$ represents
the spectral gap associated with each mode.

Gauge fields can be expanded in these modes,

\begin{equation}
A_\mu^a(x) =
\sum_n
\left(
u_{n\mu}(x) a_n^a
+
u_{n\mu}^*(x) a_n^{a\dagger}
\right).
\end{equation}

\section{Flux Tube Formation}

Consider a quark and antiquark separated by distance $r$.
The color field between them forms a flux tube.

In the Hamiltonian Crystal framework, this flux tube excites
a sequence of vacuum cells. If each cell requires energy
$\Delta E_g$ and has characteristic size $l_{\text{cell}}$,
then the number of excited cells is approximately

\begin{equation}
N \approx \frac{r}{l_{\text{cell}}}.
\end{equation}

The energy of the flux tube is therefore

\begin{equation}
E(r) = N \Delta E_g.
\end{equation}

Substituting for $N$ gives

\begin{equation}
E(r) = \frac{\Delta E_g}{l_{\text{cell}}} r .
\end{equation}

Defining the string tension

\begin{equation}
\sigma = \frac{\Delta E_g}{l_{\text{cell}}},
\end{equation}

we obtain the confinement potential

\begin{equation}
V(r) = \sigma r .
\end{equation}

\section{Rotating Flux Tube}

A hadron with angular momentum $J$ may be modeled as
a rotating flux tube.

For a string of length $r$ and tension $\sigma$,
the energy is

\begin{equation}
E = \sigma r .
\end{equation}

The angular momentum of the rotating string is

\begin{equation}
J = \frac{1}{2} \sigma r^2 .
\end{equation}

Eliminating $r$ gives

\begin{equation}
E^2 = 2\pi\sigma J .
\end{equation}

Identifying $E = m$, we obtain the Regge trajectory

\begin{equation}
m^2 = 2\pi\sigma J .
\end{equation}

\section{Numerical Estimates}

Lattice QCD gives the string tension

\begin{equation}
\sigma \approx (440 \text{ MeV})^2 \approx 0.19 \text{ GeV}^2 .
\end{equation}

The predicted Regge slope is therefore

\begin{equation}
2\pi\sigma \approx 1.2 \text{ GeV}^2 .
\end{equation}

Observed hadron trajectories have slopes near

\begin{equation}
\alpha'^{-1} \approx 1.1\text{--}1.3 \text{ GeV}^2 ,
\end{equation}

which is consistent with the prediction.

\section{Conclusion}

Within the Hamiltonian Crystal framework, confinement arises
naturally from the excitation of discrete vacuum cells.
The resulting flux tube produces a linear potential between
color charges. When the flux tube rotates, it generates the
Regge relation $m^2 \propto J$ observed in hadron spectroscopy.

This suggests that several non-perturbative features of QCD
may be understood as consequences of a discrete vacuum structure.

